SECOND REGULAR SESSION
HOUSE COMMITTEE SUBSTITUTE FOR
HOUSE BILL NOS. 2951, 2958 & 2977
103RD GENERAL ASSEMBLY
6404H.02C JOSEPH ENGLER, Chief Clerk
AN ACT
To repeal section 301.010, RSMo, and to enact in lieu thereof five new sections relating to
motor vehicle registration, with penalty provisions.
Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the state of Missouri, as follows:
Section A. Section 301.010, RSMo, is repealed and five new sections enacted in lieu
2 thereof, to be known as sections 144.465, 301.010, 301.092, 301.093, and 301.094, to read as
3 follows:
144.465. 1. The dates from August 28, 2026, to December 1, 2026, shall be
2 designated as an "amnesty period" for taxpayers in this state who did not pay state and
3 local taxes as outlined in sections 301.092 to 301.094 and who titled and registered their
4 motor vehicle, recreational vehicle or any other vehicle in another state and such
5 vehicle, under sections 301.092 to 301.094, would have been required to have been titled
6 and registered in the state of Missouri and who are delinquent in taxes and other
7 liabilities to the department of revenue arising from the purchases of said vehicles.
8 Notwithstanding any provisions of law to the contrary, with respect to all associated late
9 fees and penalties administered by the department of revenue, a taxpayer shall be
10 granted full amnesty from the assessment or payment of all such late fees and penalties
11 provided that the liabilities have arisen from a motor vehicle purchase completed before
12 August 28, 2026, and the taxpayer completes and submits a written application for such
13 amnesty to the department of revenue during the amnesty period. The department of
14 revenue shall be responsible for designing and publishing a written application for this
15 amnesty program not less than thirty days before the beginning of this amnesty period.
16 2. The department of revenue shall issue a certificate of title and registration
17 eligibility to each eligible taxpayer who submits a completed application during the
